--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>Numeric codes (<a>Int</a>)</li>
--   <li>Text identifiers (<a>Text</a>)</li>
--   <li>Objects (generic type a)</li>

--   blocks and items are identified both by numeric IDs and string

--   
--   <h2>Usage</h2>
--

--   
--   <pre>
--   -- imagine tr :: <a>TypeRep</a> exists.
--   let items = [("minecraft:stone", tr <tt>Stone), ("minecraft:dirt", tr </tt>Dirt)]
--   case <a>mkreg0</a> items of
--     <a>Just</a> reg -&gt; -- Use registry
--     <a>Nothing</a> -&gt; -- Handle duplicate keys

--   
--   <pre>

-- | A "registry" type maintaining a triple link between codes, identifiers
--   and objects.
--   
--   The registry is immutable after creation and provides efficient
--   lookups in both directions:
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>From numeric code to object (using <a>IntMap</a>)</li>
--   <li>From text identifier to numeric code (using <a>HashMap</a>)</li>
--   </ul>
--   
--   <h2>Implementation Notes</h2>
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>code -&gt; object mapping uses lazy <a>IntMap</a> since object
--   types may be large</li>
--   <li>identifier -&gt; code mapping uses strict <a>HashMap</a> for text
--   lookups</li>
--   <li>Registry cannot be modified after creation (updates planned for
--   future)</li>
--   </ul>

-- | Create a registry with a transformation function applied to values.
